goals.question: What is the overall trend of unemployment rate across all industries from 2000 to 2010?
goals.visualization: Line chart of unemployment rate against year
goals.rationale: This visualization will help to identify if there is an overall increase or decrease in unemployment rate across all industries over the years.

goals.question: Which industry has the highest unemployment rate?
goals.visualization: Bar chart of unemployment rate against industry
goals.rationale: This visualization will help to identify the industry with the highest unemployment rate and compare it with other industries.

goals.question: What is the distribution of unemployment count across all industries?
goals.rationale: This visualization will help to identify the range of unemployment count across all industries and if there are any outliers.

goals.question: What is the relationship between unemployment count and unemployment rate?
goals.visualization: Scatter plot of unemployment count against unemployment rate
goals.rationale: This visualization will help to identify if there is a correlation between unemployment count and unemployment rate.

goals.question: What is the trend of unemployment rate for the Education and Health industry?

goals.rationale: This visualization will help to identify if there is an overall increase or decrease in unemployment rate for the Education and Health industry over the years.

import matplotlib.pyplot as plt
import pandas as pd

def plot(data: pd.DataFrame):
    data['date'] = pd.to_datetime(data['date'], format='%Y-%m-%d', errors='coerce')
    data = data.sort_values(by='date')
    data = data.groupby(['year'])['rate'].mean().reset_index()
    plt.plot(data['year'], data['rate'], color='blue')
    plt.axhline(y=data['rate'].mean(), color='red', linestyle='--', label='Mean')
    plt.title('What is the overall trend of unemployment rate across all industries from 2000 to 2010?', wrap=True)
    plt.legend()
    return plt

chart = plot(data)

import matplotlib.pyplot as plt
import pandas as pd
def plot(data: pd.DataFrame):
    data['date'] = pd.to_datetime(data['date'], format='%Y-%m-%d', errors='coerce')
    data = data.dropna(subset=['date'])
    data = data.sort_values(by='rate', ascending=False)
    top_industry = data.iloc[0]['series']
    top_rate = data.iloc[0]['rate']
    plt.bar(data['series'], data['rate'])
    plt.axhline(y=top_rate, color='r', linestyle='-')
    plt.legend([f'Top Industry: {top_industry}, Top Rate: {top_rate:.2f}'])
    plt.xticks(rotation=90)
    plt.title('Which industry has the highest unemployment rate?', wrap=True)
    return plt;

chart = plot(data)

import matplotlib.pyplot as plt
import pandas as pd
def plot(data: pd.DataFrame):
    data['count'].plot(kind='hist', bins=50, color='blue', edgecolor='black', alpha=0.7)
    plt.axvline(data['count'].median(), color='red', linestyle='dashed', linewidth=1, label='Median: {:.2f}'.format(data['count'].median()))
    plt.title('What is the distribution of unemployment count across all industries?', wrap=True)
    plt.legend()
    return plt;

chart = plot(data)

import matplotlib.pyplot as plt
import pandas as pd
def plot(data: pd.DataFrame):
    data['date'] = pd.to_datetime(data['date'], format='%Y-%m-%d', errors='coerce')
    fig, ax = plt.subplots(figsize=(10, 6))
    ax.scatter(data['count'], data['rate'], alpha=0.5)
    ax.set_xlabel('Unemployment Count')
    ax.set_ylabel('Unemployment Rate')
    plt.title('What is the relationship between unemployment count and unemployment rate?', wrap=True)
    return plt;

chart = plot(data)

def plot(data: pd.DataFrame):
    data['date'] = pd.to_datetime(data['date'], format='%Y-%m-%d', errors='coerce')
    edu_health = data[data['series'] == 'Education and Health']
    edu_health = edu_health.groupby('year')['rate'].mean().reset_index()
    plt.plot(edu_health['year'], edu_health['rate'], color='blue')
    plt.title('What is the trend of unemployment rate for the Education and Health industry?')
    plt.xlabel('Year')
    plt.ylabel('Unemployment Rate')
    plt.axhline(y=edu_health['rate'].median(), color='red', linestyle='--', label='Median')
    plt.legend()
    return plt

chart = plot(data)
